Sarynth 04-Mar-17 08:28 AM
error('string', number) anyone ever used number, just discovered it, pretty nifty for custom libraries
Keril Artemov 04-Mar-17 08:29 AM
what does it do
Sarynth 04-Mar-17 08:29 AM
It points back number levels in the call stack.
So if you have a custom function like doTheThing(x) if x is not a string then error('needs string dummy', 2) and the file/line error will be the caller. And if you have nested functions in your library, you can do , 3 or whatever if the offender is another level up.
Keril Artemov 04-Mar-17 08:31 AM
that's kinda weird to do manually
Sarynth 04-Mar-17 08:32 AM
It's useful for decoupled libraries.
Or really abstracted libraries.
For example, I've got my own Events library, super simple. But if I screw up, and pass in a string rather than a callback function, error('needs function, 2) will point to the bad line, rather than the events library.
